# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: scylladb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Avinash Lakshman, a co-author of Amazon's Dynamo, and Prashant Malik developed Cassandra at Facebook to support the inbox search functionality.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Facebook released Cassandra as open-source software on Google Code in July 2008.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] In March 2009, it became an Apache Incubator project and on February 17, 2010, it graduated to a top-level project.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] The developers at Facebook named their database after Cassandra, the mythological Trojan prophetess, referencing her curse of making prophecies that were never believed.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Cassandra uses a distributed architecture where all nodes perform identical functions, eliminating single points of failure.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] The system employs configurable replication strategies to distribute data across clusters, providing redundancy and disaster recovery capabilities.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] The system is capable of linear scaling, which increases read and write throughput with the addition of new nodes, while maintaining continuous service.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Cassandra is categorized as an AP (Availability and Partition Tolerance) system, emphasizing availability and partition tolerance over consistency.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] While it offers tunable consistency levels for both read and write operations, its architecture makes it less suitable for use cases requiring strict consistency guarantees.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Additionally, Cassandra's compatibility with Hadoop and related tools allows for integration with existing big data processing workflows.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Eventual consistency is maintained using tombstones to manage reads, upserts, and deletes.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] The system's query capabilities have notable limitations.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Cassandra does not support advanced query patterns such as multi-table JOINs, ad hoc aggregations, or complex queries.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] These limitations stem from its distributed architecture, which optimizes for scalability and availability rather than complex query operations.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] As a wide-column store, Cassandra combines features of both key-value and tabular database systems.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] It implements a partitioned row store model with adjustable consistency levels.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] The following table compares Cassandra and relational database management systems (RDBMS).
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] A keyspace in Cassandra is analogous to a database in relational systems.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] It contains multiple tables and manages configuration information, including replication strategy and user-defined types (UDTs).
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Tables (formerly called column families prior to CQL 3) are containers for rows of data.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Each table has a name and configuration information for its stored data.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Tables may be created, dropped, or altered at run-time without blocking updates and queries.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Each row is identified by a primary key and contains columns.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] The first component of a table's primary key is the partition key; within a partition, rows are clustered by the remaining columns of the key.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Unlike traditional RDBMS tables, rows within the same table can have varying columns, providing a flexible structure.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] This flexibility distinguishes Cassandra from relational databases, as not all columns need to be specified for each row.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Other columns may be indexed separately from the primary key.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Cassandra uses a Log Structured Merge Tree (LSM tree) index to optimize write throughput, in contrast to the B-tree indexes used by most databases.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Every operation (create/update/delete) generates a new entry, with deletes handled via "tombstones".
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] While common in many databases, tombstones can cause performance degradation in delete-heavy workloads.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Cassandra Query Language (CQL) is the interface for accessing Cassandra, as an alternative to the traditional Structured Query Language (SQL).
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] CQL adds an abstraction layer that hides implementation details of this structure and provides native syntaxes for collections and other common encodings.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Language drivers are available for Java (JDBC), Python (DBAPI2), Node.JS (DataStax), Go (gocql), and C++.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] The key space in Cassandra is a namespace that defines data replication across nodes.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Therefore, replication is defined at the key space level.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Cassandra uses a peer-to-peer gossip protocol for cluster communication.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] The system uses vector clocks to track information currency and ignore outdated state data.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] This design eliminates single points of failure while maintaining cluster-wide consistency of operational knowledge.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Cassandra employs the Phi Accrual Failure Detector to manage node failures during cluster operation.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Through this system, each node independently assesses the availability of other nodes during gossip communication.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] When a node fails to respond, it is "convicted" and removed from write operations, though it can rejoin the cluster upon resuming heartbeat signals.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] To maintain data integrity during node outages, Cassandra uses a "hinted handoff" mechanism.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] When writing to an offline node, the coordinator node temporarily stores the write data as a "hint." Once the offline node returns to service, these hints are forwarded to restore data consistency.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Notably, Cassandra only permanently removes nodes through explicit administrative decommissioning or rebuilding, preventing temporary communication failures or restarts from triggering unnecessary data rebalancing.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Cassandra is a Java-based system that can be managed and monitored via Java Management Extensions (JMX).
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] The JMX-compliant *Nodetool* utility, for instance, can be used to manage a Cassandra cluster.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Nodetool also offers a number of commands to return Cassandra metrics pertaining to disk usage, latency, compaction, garbage collection, and more.
[src:scylladb/apache-cassandra] Since the release of Cassandra 2.0.2 in 2013, measures of several metrics are produced via the Dropwizard metrics framework, and may be queried via JMX using tools such as JConsole or passed to external monitoring systems via Dropwizard-compatible reporter plugins.
[src:scylladb/blob-readme-md] Scylla is the real-time big data database that is API-compatible with Apache Cassandra and Amazon DynamoDB.
[src:scylladb/blob-readme-md] Scylla embraces a shared-nothing approach that increases throughput and storage capacity to realize order-of-magnitude performance improvements and reduce hardware costs.
[src:scylladb/blob-readme-md] For more information, please see the ScyllaDB web site.
[src:scylladb/blob-readme-md] Scylla is fairly fussy about its build environment, requiring very recent versions of the C++23 compiler and of many libraries to build.
[src:scylladb/blob-readme-md] The document HACKING.md includes detailed information on building and developing Scylla, but to get Scylla building quickly on (almost) any build machine, Scylla offers a frozen toolchain.
[src:scylladb/blob-readme-md] This is a pre-configured Docker image which includes recent versions of all the required compilers, libraries and build tools.
[src:scylladb/blob-readme-md] Using the frozen toolchain allows you to avoid changing anything in your build machine to meet Scylla's requirements - you just need to meet the frozen toolchain's prerequisites (mostly, Docker or Podman being available).
[src:scylladb/blob-readme-md] This will start a Scylla node with one CPU core allocated to it and data files stored in the `tmp` directory.
[src:scylladb/blob-readme-md] The `--developer-mode` is needed to disable the various checks Scylla performs at startup to ensure the machine is configured for maximum performance (not relevant on development workstations).
[src:scylladb/blob-readme-md] Please note that you need to run Scylla with `dbuild` if you built it with the frozen toolchain.
[src:scylladb/blob-readme-md] By default, Scylla is compatible with Apache Cassandra and its API - CQL.
[src:scylladb/blob-readme-md] There is also support for the API of Amazon DynamoDB™, which needs to be enabled and configured in order to be used.
[src:scylladb/blob-readme-md] For more information on how to enable the DynamoDB™ API in Scylla, and the current compatibility of this feature as well as Scylla-specific extensions, see Alternator and Getting started with Alternator.
[src:scylladb/blob-readme-md] Seastar documentation can be found here.
[src:scylladb/blob-readme-md] Training material and online courses can be found at Scylla University.
[src:scylladb/blob-readme-md] The courses are free, self-paced and include hands-on examples.
[src:scylladb/blob-readme-md] They cover a variety of topics including Scylla data modeling, administration, architecture, basic NoSQL concepts, using drivers for application development, Scylla setup, failover, compactions, multi-datacenters and how Scylla integrates with third-party applications.
[src:scylladb/blob-readme-md] If you want to report a bug or submit a pull request or a patch, please read the contribution guidelines.
[src:scylladb/blob-readme-md] If you are a developer working on Scylla, please read the developer guidelines.
[src:scylladb/page] ScyllaDB is a high-performance NoSQL database optimized for speed and scalability.
[src:scylladb/page] Start developing with ScyllaDB here, with sample models, connection instructions and more.
