[src:scylladb/page] There are several webinars to choose from.
[src:scylladb/scylladb] ScyllaDB uses a sharded design on each node, meaning that each CPU core handles a different subset of data.
[src:scylladb/scylladb] Cores do not share data, but rather communicate explicitly when they need to.
[src:scylladb/scylladb] The ScyllaDB authors claim that this design allows ScyllaDB to achieve much better performance on modern NUMA SMP machines, and to scale very well with the number of cores.
[src:scylladb/scylladb] They have measured as much as 2 million requests per second on a single machine, and also claim that a ScyllaDB cluster can serve as many requests as a Cassandra cluster 10 times its size – and do so with lower latencies.
[src:scylladb/scylladb] Independent testing has not always been able to confirm such 10-fold throughput improvements, and sometimes measured smaller speedups, such as 2x.
[src:scylladb/scylladb] A 2017 benchmark from Samsung observed the 10x speedup on high-end machines – the Samsung benchmark reported that ScyllaDB outperformed Cassandra on a cluster of 24-core machines by a margin of 10–37x depending on the YCSB workload.
[src:scylladb/scylladb] ScyllaDB is available on-premises, on major public cloud providers, or as a DBaaS (ScyllaDB Cloud).
[src:scylladb/scylladb] ScyllaDB was started in December 2014 by the startup Cloudius Systems (later renamed ScyllaDB Inc.), previously known for having created OSv.
[src:scylladb/scylladb] Co-founders were Avi Kivity and Dor Laor.
[src:scylladb/scylladb] ScyllaDB was released as open source in September 2015, under the AGPL license.
[src:scylladb/scylladb] In December 2024, ScyllaDB moved to a source available license.
[src:scylladb/scylladb] Its source code and development process is still open to the public on public GitHub repositories, but usage on a cluster beyond a certain size requires purchasing a license.
[src:scylladb/scylladb] In 2026, ScyllaDB announced vector database support.
[src:scylladb/wide-column-store] A **wide-column store** (or **extensible record store**) is a type of NoSQL database.
[src:scylladb/wide-column-store] It uses tables, rows, and columns, but unlike a relational database, the names and format of the columns can vary from row to row in the same table.
[src:scylladb/wide-column-store] A wide-column store can be interpreted as a two-dimensional key–value store.
[src:scylladb/wide-column-store] Google's Bigtable is one of the prototypical examples of a wide-column store.
[src:scylladb/wide-column-store] Wide-column stores such as Bigtable and Apache Cassandra are not column stores in the original sense of the term, since their two-level structures do not use a columnar data layout.
[src:scylladb/wide-column-store] In genuine column stores, a columnar data layout is adopted such that each column is stored separately on disk.
[src:scylladb/wide-column-store] Wide-column stores do often support the notion of column families that are stored separately.
[src:scylladb/wide-column-store] However, each such column family typically contains multiple columns that are used together, similar to traditional relational database tables.
[src:scylladb/wide-column-store] Within a given column family, all data is stored in a row-by-row fashion, such that the columns for a given row are stored together, rather than each column being stored separately.
[src:scylladb/wide-column-store] Wide-column stores that support column families are also known as *column family databases*.
